SIMPLE: rehearse
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Rehearse
<hw>Re*hearse"</hw> <pr>(r?*h?rs")</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos>
<vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos> <conjf>Rehearsed</conjf>
<pr>(-h?rst")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Rehearsing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>rehercen</ets>,
<ets>rehersen</ets>, OF. <ets>reherser</ets>, <ets>rehercier</ets>, to
harrow over again; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>hercier</ets> to
harrow, fr. <ets>herce</ets> a harrow, F. <ets>herse</ets>. See
<er>Hearse</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To repeat, as what has been
already said; to tell over again; to recite.</def>
<rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>When the words were heard which David spake, they
<qex>rehearsed</qex> them before Saul.</q> <rj><qau>1 Sam. xvii.
31.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To narrate; to relate; to tell.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Rehearse</qex> the righteous acts of the Lord.</q>
<rj><qau>Judg. . v. 11.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To recite or repeat in private for experiment and
improvement, before a public representation; <as>as, to
<ex>rehearse</ex> a tragedy</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>To cause to rehearse; to instruct by
rehearsal.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He has been <qex>rehearsed</qex> by Madame Defarge as to his
having seen her.</q> <rj><qau>Dickens.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To recite; recapitulate; recount; detail;
describe; tell; relate; narrate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rehearse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Rehearse
<hw>Re*hearse"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To recite or repeat something
for practice.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧There will we <xex>rehearse</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Rehearser</ent>⟦br⟧
